<img class="size-full wp-image-3552" src="http://dailyuv.net/dailyuv/wp-content/uploads/sites/20/2015/09/telluride1.jpg" alt="Telluride, Colorado, comes to Hanover." width="1200" height="900">

Once a year Upper Valley residents can brag to their flatlander friends that they've seen a great new movie weeks before everyone else.

That annual event—the Telluride at Dartmouth Festival—begins on Friday, Sept. 18 and runs through Thursday, Sept. 24. (No films shown on Monday, Sept. 21.)

<img class="wp-image-3400 size-medium" src="http://dailyuv.net/dailyuv/wp-content/uploads/sites/20/2015/09/HeNamedMeMalala1-300x225.jpg" alt="Malala-Kenya-EJ-6.jpg" width="300" height="225">

The festival opens with <a href="https://hop.dartmouth.edu/online/telluridemalala">He Named me Malala</a>, Dave Guggenheim's documentary about the 11-year-old girl who was shot in the head by the Taliban.

<img class="wp-image-3402 size-medium" src="http://dailyuv.net/dailyuv/wp-content/uploads/sites/20/2015/09/Spotlights-300x200.jpg" alt="S_07041.CR2" width="300" height="200">

Saturday's movie is <a href="https://hop.dartmouth.edu/online/tellurideSPOTLIGHT">Spotlight</a>. Liev Schreiber, Michael Keaton, Mark Ruffalo and Rachel McAdams star in film about the Boston Globe's investigation of a priest's sexual misconduct.

<img class="wp-image-3398 size-medium" src="http://dailyuv.net/dailyuv/wp-content/uploads/sites/20/2015/09/Suffragette-300x193.jpg" alt="Suffragette" width="300" height="193">

<a href="https://hop.dartmouth.edu/online/tellurideSUFFRAGETTE">Suffragette</a>, a film about the women's right movement in the early 20th century, stars Carey Mulligan, Anne-Marie Duff and Helena Bonham Carter and will be shown on Sunday.

<img class="wp-image-3403 size-medium" src="http://dailyuv.net/dailyuv/wp-content/uploads/sites/20/2015/09/IxcanulVolcano2-300x123.jpg" alt="IxcanulVolcano2" width="300" height="123">

Tuesday's film <a href="https://hop.dartmouth.edu/online/tellurideixcanulvolcano">Ixcanul Volcano</a>, already a winner a several prominent film festivals, offers a glimpse of contemporary culture in rural Guatemala.

<img class="wp-image-3404 size-medium" src="http://dailyuv.net/dailyuv/wp-content/uploads/sites/20/2015/09/Rams1-300x126.jpg" alt="Rams1" width="300" height="126">

<a href="https://hop.dartmouth.edu/online/telluriderams">Ram</a>s, an Icelandic comedy about feuding septuagenarian brothers and sheep screens, airs on Wednesday.

<img class="wp-image-3405 size-medium" src="http://dailyuv.net/dailyuv/wp-content/uploads/sites/20/2015/09/45-Yearss-300x199.jpg" alt="45 Years" width="300" height="199">

Closing the festival on Thursday is<a href="https://hop.dartmouth.edu/online/telluride45years"> 45 Years</a>, starring Charlotte Rampling and Tom Courtenay as a long-married couple who confronting uncertainties of what seems to have been a happy marriage.

For maximum bragging rights buy a series pass for $60 and get the bonus of priority seating. Passes for Hopkins Center members went on sale Sept. 8. Sales to the general public went on sale Sept. 9. Tickets for individual films are $12. <a href="https://hop.dartmouth.edu/online/box_office">Passes and tickets can be bought online </a>or by phone 603-646-2422.

You can see times for these films -- and many other movies available in the Upper Valley -- in <a href="https://dailyuv.com/events/?category=Movies&amp;location=All%20Communities&amp;r=1442239623" target="_blank">dailyUV's event listings</a>. 
